@@ -0,0 +1,110 @@
+# Note from the runtime team → inline-3d browser agent
+
+**Re: does the new `XR_DXR_canvas_rect` (#697) extension help the browser weave path?**
+**From:** displayxr-runtime, branch `feat/697-canvas-rect-windowless` (built + lint-clean, **not merged** — parked pending a real consumer).
+**We need:** a yes/no + which process, so we decide *merge* vs *leave parked*.
+
+---
+
+## What the extension does (30-second version)
+
+Today the runtime learns *where on the 3D panel* a producer's content lands — which
+it needs for both **weave phase** (lenticular interlace is a function of absolute
+screen position) and **canvas-scoped Kooima** (off-axis projection framed to the
+content rect) — by reading a **bound OS window's** client rect (`GetClientRect` +
+`ClientToScreen`) every frame. The HWND is a *position/phase anchor*, never a render
+target.
+
+`XR_DXR_canvas_rect` lets a **windowless** producer **declare that rect directly**
+instead of binding a window:
+
+- `XrCanvasRectBindingDXR` (chained on `xrCreateSession`) — seed the rect.
+- `xrSetCanvasRectDXR(session, &rectPx)` — update it whenever the content moves/resizes.
+- `rectPx` is **display-relative device pixels** (origin = panel top-left; the runtime
+  already knows the panel's desktop origin via `XR_DXR_display_info`).
+
+The runtime feeds that rect through the *same* `get_window_metrics` producer the HWND
+path uses, so `canvasRectPx` / Kooima / weave phase all come out identical — with **no
+window**. The only thing lost vs. a bound window is OS *self-tracking*: the app owns
+rect updates (call the setter on move/resize). Drag phase-snap still works — it's
+`xrWeaveSnapWindowRectDXR` (already pure absolute-screen-coords, driven by a
+service-owned probe window, never the app's HWND).
+
+Implemented on the **D3D11 in-process** and **D3D11 service/IPC** compositors.
+
+## Why we're asking you specifically
+
+The extension only earns its keep for a producer that has **no usable OS window** but
+*is* compositing to a **known on-panel rect**. Anything with a real top-level HWND is
+already served by `XR_DXR_win32_window_binding` or `XR_DXR_weave`'s
+`xrWeaveBindWindowDXR` (bind a window + submit a window-relative rect, #625).
+
+Your integration is the one candidate where "no usable window" might be literally true.
+We see `components/displayxr/gpu/displayxr_weave_gpu.{cc,h}` (GPU-process weave) and
+`components/displayxr/browser/displayxr_weave_client.*` / `displayxr_weaver_impl.*`.
+
+## The questions (what would settle it)
+
+1. **Which process issues the weave / talks to the runtime?** The browser process
+   (which has the tab's top-level `HWND`) or the **GPU/Viz process** (which composites
+   all content and owns **no per-element window**)?
+2. **Today, does that path hand the runtime an HWND for phase/position?** If yes —
+   whose window, and is it a real usable one? If no — how does it currently get correct
+   weave phase and off-axis framing (or does it run display-scoped / fixed-fullscreen)?
+3. **Per inline-3d element** (a `<model>` / WebXR region that scrolls within a page):
+   can you cheaply produce that element's **absolute on-panel rect in device px** each
+   frame (page layout → screen)? That's the exact input `xrSetCanvasRectDXR` wants.
+4. **Would "declare a screen-relative rect, no HWND" simplify your integration**
+   vs. binding a window — especially if the weave lives GPU-process-side where there's
+   no window to bind? Or does `XR_DXR_weave` bindWindow+rect already fit because you do
+   have a usable HWND at the integration point?
+
+If the answer to (1) is "GPU/Viz process, no window" and (3) is "yes, we have the
+rect," then `XR_DXR_canvas_rect` is the clean anchor and we'll finish + merge it (and
+add the symmetric `xrWeaveBindRectDXR` to the weave service so the per-element
+synchronous weave can also run windowless). If you already bind a usable HWND, this is
+redundant and we'll park the branch.
+
+## Pointers (runtime side)
+
+- Header: `src/external/openxr_includes/openxr/XR_DXR_canvas_rect.h`
+- Spec: `docs/specs/extensions/XR_DXR_canvas_rect.md`
+- App-facing framing: `docs/getting-started/app-classes.md` (the `#697` section)
+- Reference exerciser (shared texture + rect, **no HWND**):
+  `test_apps/texture/cube_canvasrect_d3d11_win`
+- Related: `XR_DXR_weave.h` (`xrWeaveBindWindowDXR` / `xrWeaveSubmitDXR` /
+  `xrWeaveSnapWindowRectDXR`, #625) — the windowed present-owner weave service this
+  generalizes.
+
+Reply inline in this file (or ping the runtime side) with answers to 1–4. Thanks!
+
+---
+
+## UPDATE (after hardware test — important caveat)
+
+We built the full runtime path + a windowless exerciser (shared texture + rect, no
+HWND) and ran it on the Leia panel. Result: **flat / no 3D**, and the reason is
+decisive and vendor-side:
+
+- The runtime plumbing works: the declared display-relative rect reaches the DP as
+  its weave canvas (`canvas=(16,72 1280x720)`), the panel switches to 3D mode, and
+  Kooima is canvas-scoped.
+- **BUT** the vendor DP (Leia SR weaver) reports **both eye positions identical**
+  (collapsed to the single nominal-viewer point) when there is **no bound HWND** —
+  so there is zero stereo disparity and the image is flat, before phase even matters.
+- Per ADR-007/019 the runtime never synthesizes eyes and never weaves — distinct
+  per-eye positions and absolute weave phase are BOTH the vendor DP's job, and the
+  SR SDK weaver's only positional/tracking input is `setWindowHandle(HWND)` (no
+  `setScreenRect` / `setOffset`). So a runtime-only canvas rect is
+  **necessary-but-not-sufficient**.
+
+**Implication for you:** if your weave integration is genuinely windowless (GPU/Viz
+process, no HWND), `XR_DXR_canvas_rect` alone will NOT give you correct 3D on the
+current Leia DP — it needs a **coupled vendor-DP change first** (SR SDK / Leia plugin
+support for windowless operation: distinct eyes + absolute phase from a supplied
+screen rect instead of an HWND). If instead you DO have a usable HWND at the weave
+call site, use `XR_DXR_weave` bindWindow+rect (#625) and you're fine today.
+
+So the honest state: the runtime branch is **parked**. It becomes worth finishing
+only if (a) you confirm a windowless integration point AND (b) the vendor adds
+windowless DP support. Your answers to 1–4 still tell us whether (a) holds.
